<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="427" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1851,2020]" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1851,1876]" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is known from the upper reaches of the Ping River (one of two main tributaries of the Chao Phraya River) drainage in northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[725,825,1887,1912]" name="Thailand" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[842,913,1887,1912]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1591,1613]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,207,1569]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,195,1569]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Map showing collecting localities of Exostoma species in Thailand examined in this study. The type localities of E. effrenum and E. peregrinator are shown much further apart than they really are in order to easily distinguish between the two symbols." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230833/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">
Fig. 
<number box="[897,913,1887,1911]" pageId="7" pageNumber="427" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). The record from the Doi Inthanon National Park in Chiang Mai Province, 
<collectingCountry box="[496,598,1923,1948]" name="Thailand" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, is based on photographs of specimens (not preserved; 
<figureCitation box="[1223,1290,1923,1948]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1754,1776]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,769,1732]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,769,1732]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Exostoma effrenum, live individual approx. 100 mm SL from Doi Inthanon National Park, Chiang Mai Province, Thailand (specimen not preserved). Photograph by Nonn Panitvong." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230835/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">
Fig. 
<number box="[1276,1290,1923,1948]" pageId="7" pageNumber="427" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
) referable to this species we have examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="428" pageId="7" pageNumber="427" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1851,2020]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="428" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1995,2020]" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet comes from the Latin adjective 
<emphasis box="[937,1026,1995,2019]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="427">effrenus</emphasis>
, meaning unbridled. This is used in allusion to the condition of the adipose fin being distinctly separate from the upper principal caudal-fin rays in this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
